description: Titles of high-ranking officials in the Catholic Church, such as Cardinals, Cardinals and Archbishops, typically denoted by specific words.
The token "Pope" often refers to the head of the Catholic Church, often used in proper nouns, titles, and in context to the church or the Vatican.
The text features various mentions of holidays and celebrations, particularly Easter, Passover, and Pentecost, often in the context of church services, traditions, and related events or activities.
Abbreviations of "Saint" preceding proper nouns, typically in the names of churches, people, or locations.
The token "Bapt" is often part of the word "Baptist", referring to Baptist churches or the Baptist denomination, and occasionally part of the word "baptize" or "baptism".
A preposition, often "of", commonly used in the names of churches, organizations, or institutions, usually connecting a descriptive phrase to the main entity.
The token "Catholic" is often used to describe a noun that is related to the Catholic faith or church, typically used in a formal or official context.
The token "worship" is often used in the context of religion, referring to the act of revering or honoring a deity, and is often found in phrases related to prayer, church, or ritual.
Prepositional phrases, often with "of", "in", or "with", are used to express relationships or possession, especially in a Christian context, often referencing Jesus Christ or the body of the church.
The token "St" is often used as an abbreviation for "Saint" in names of locations, such as cities or churches.
Formal or official names of events, places, days of the week, and time, including funerals, churches, and other public events.

Emphasis is placed on words related to specific churches, beliefs, or organizations, such as "Mormon", "LDS", "Scientology", "Watchtower", and "Jehovah's Witnesses", to highlight their connection to the associated ideas or events.
"CH" appears to be a frequent substring in proper nouns and abbreviations, often representing "Church" or a component of a chemical formula, but also appears in various other contexts.

Titles and honorifics of high-ranking officials in the Catholic Church, such as Cardinal, Archbishop, Bishop, and Pope, are often highlighted, sometimes along with conjunctions, prepositions, and articles that accompany them.
Names of Christian denominations or churches, often used as adjectives to describe institutions, events, or concepts.
References to the Presbyterian Church or its affiliates.
A person who leads a Christian church or performs religious functions.
Various tokens of organizational or grammatical function, such as prepositions, conjunctions, and articles, found in the context of births, deaths, marriages, and church-related records.

The extracted tokens are typically parts of a title or organization name, often relating to churches, civic organizations, or charities, which may include ranks or positions within these organizations.
Words related to the study, discussion, or profession of theology, often appearing in the context of education, discussion, or the church.
